Introduction to tidyverse

The tidyverse package is a collection of R packages:

  • dplyr: data manipulation
  • tidyr: reshaping/tidying data
  • ggplot2: visualization
  • tibble: modern rethinking of data.frame
  • readr, stringr …
install.packages("tidyverse")
library(tidyverse)

Brief introduction of tibble

  • Almost equal to data.frame
  • No row names:
    • has_rownames() to check
    • remove_rownames() to remove
    • rownames_to_column() to add it as a new column
  • Better subsetting:
    • Always returns a tibble
    • no partial matching
  • Better printing …

The dplyr package

Typically we need to explore and prepare data for analysis:

  • create summary statistics for variables and individuals.
  • individuals that do not meet certain criteria need to be removed.
  • create new variables.
  • do multiple things at the same time, eg. subsetting, creating, extracting.

dplyr provide a clean and nice syntax to perform these!

Commonly-used dplyr functions

“verb” functions in dplyr:

  • select()
  • filter()
  • mutate()
  • summarize()
  • group_by()

When multiple packages are loaded, it would be better to add dplyr:: in front of these functions to avoid function conflicts.

select(): subsetting data column wise

  • select() allows you to select columns (or variables) in a data frame.
  • select(x, y) means selecting variable y from data frame x.
  • Note: y can be a vector of column names or numerical positions in the data frame.

select(): in action

select(diamonds, carat, price) # extract carat and price

select(): a simpler way to exact columns

When we have hundards or even thousands of columns, it would less efficient to manually select columns

so it would be better if we could select columns based on some conditions:

diamonds_4c <- select(diamonds, starts_with("c"))
head(diamonds_4c)

select(): a simpler way to exact columns

More options for select():

  • starts_with(): Start with a literal string
  • ends_with(): End with a literal string
  • contains(): Contains a literal string
  • everything(): Select all columns

Or select with self-defined condition:

select_if(diamonds, is.numeric)[1, ]
## # A tibble: 1 × 7
##   carat depth table price     x     y     z
##   <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <int> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1  0.23  61.5    55   326  3.95  3.98  2.43

select(): remove columns

Now if we want to remove 4C columns and keep other columns in diamonds, usually for data.frame would do something like

diamonds$cut <- NULL
...

For select() it is:

diamonds_r4c <- select(diamonds, -cut, -color, -clarity, -carat)

Or even better:

diamonds_r4c <- select(diamonds, -starts_with("c"))
diamonds_r4c[1, ]
## # A tibble: 1 × 6
##   depth table price     x     y     z
##   <dbl> <dbl> <int> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1  61.5    55   326  3.95  3.98  2.43

filter(): Large diamonds

Now if another customer would like to buy diamonds that large enough (all of x, y, z > 3), could you select them?

Use if_all() to select columns and apply the same condition to all of them, this will keep rows that all of the selected columns satisfy the condition:

filter(diamonds, if_all(c(x, y, z), function(col) col > 3))[1, ]
## # A tibble: 1 × 10
##   carat cut   color clarity depth table price     x     y     z
##   <dbl> <ord> <ord> <ord>   <dbl> <dbl> <int> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1   0.7 Ideal E     SI1      62.5    57  2757   5.7  5.72  3.57

Similarily if we want to keep rows where at least one of the selected columns satisfied the condition, then use if_any():

filter(diamonds, if_any(c(x, y, z), function(col) col > 3))[1, ]
## # A tibble: 1 × 10
##   carat cut   color clarity depth table price     x     y     z
##   <dbl> <ord> <ord> <ord>   <dbl> <dbl> <int> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1  0.23 Ideal E     SI2      61.5    55   326  3.95  3.98  2.43

mutate(): change/create a variable

  • mutate(x, y=args): add a column y to data frame x, where y = args. If y already exists, then replace y with y = args.
  • You can change/create multiple variables using one pass of mutate().

Example:

mutate(): Switching metric for sizes

Suppose your manager wants you to switch the unit for x, y, z from mm to cm, then we could switch them one by one, or we could achieve this by one line of code:

diamonds_cm <- mutate(diamonds, across(c(x, y, z), function (col) col / 10))
head(diamonds_cm)

mutate(): Switching metric for sizes

across() is a convenient way to operate simultaneously for multiple columns, a simple approximation (just for intuitive understanding) could be:

across <- function(columns, func) {
  for (column in columns) {
    columns[column] <- func(column)
  }
  return columns
}

Note that across() is helper function, thus we can’t use it outside of mutate() (group_by(), filter() etc.)

summarize(): Summarize the data

  • summarize() creates a new table of summary statistics (Maps a vector to a scalar).
  • summarize(x, y = f(z)): Apply f to the variable z in x and call it y.
  • Some example functions: sum(z), mean(z), median(z), min(z), max(z).
  • Allows user-defined functions.
  • summarise() works as well.

Example:

summarize(diamonds, avg_price = mean(price))
## # A tibble: 1 × 1
##   avg_price
##       <dbl>
## 1     3933.

summarize(): in action

  • allows user-defined functions (takes a vector and returns a scalar)
ssq <- function(x){
  return(sum(x^2))
}
summarize(diamonds, ssq_price = ssq(price))
## # A tibble: 1 × 1
##       ssq_price
##           <dbl>
## 1 1692758457943

summarize(): in action

  • can output multiple summaries!
summarize(diamonds,
          mean_price = mean(price),
          median_price = median(price))
## # A tibble: 1 × 2
##   mean_price median_price
##        <dbl>        <dbl>
## 1      3933.         2401

summarize(): apply multiple function for multiple columns at once

summarize(diamonds,
          me_price = mean(price),
          medi_price = median(price),
          me_carat = mean(carat),
          medi_carat = median(carat))
## # A tibble: 1 × 4
##   me_price medi_price me_carat medi_carat
##      <dbl>      <dbl>    <dbl>      <dbl>
## 1    3933.       2401    0.798        0.7
summarise(diamonds, 
          across(c(price, carat), 
                 list(me = mean, medi = median), 
                 .names = "{.fn}_{.col}"))
## # A tibble: 1 × 4
##   me_price medi_price me_carat medi_carat
##      <dbl>      <dbl>    <dbl>      <dbl>
## 1    3933.       2401    0.798        0.7

summarize(): summarize the data

  • summarize() takes a vector and return a scalar value and thus disregards other variables in the data.
  • Sometimes, we are interested in looking at group-specific summaries.
  • E.g: Average price based on cut.

group_by(): group the data

  • Now any functions we apply will be based on the grouping, eg. summarize(), filter(), mutate(), etc.

group_by(): in action

diamonds_cut <- group_by(diamonds, cut)
summarize(diamonds_cut,
          mean_price = mean(price),
          median_price = median(price))

## 5 Ideal          3458.        1810

Applying more than one transformation

  • Oftentimes, we want to apply multiple transformation to the data, eg. filter(), mutate(), etc.
  • dplyr provides an easier and cleaner way to apply multiple transformations through pipe function!

The pipe function

The pipe function |> (or %>%) is essentially a transformation of a data frame to another data frame.

Think about it as an assembly line!

Excercises (revisited)

diamonds_cut <- group_by(diamonds, cut)
summarize(diamonds_cut,
          mean_price = mean(price),
          median_price = median(price))
## # A tibble: 5 × 3
##   cut       mean_price median_price
##   <ord>          <dbl>        <dbl>
## 1 Fair           4359.        3282 
## 2 Good           3929.        3050.
## 3 Very Good      3982.        2648 
## 4 Premium        4584.        3185 
## 5 Ideal          3458.        1810

Exercise (revisited): use pipe function

diamonds |>
  group_by(cut) |>
  summarize(mean_price = mean(price),

dplyr: Merging data

  • inner_join(x, y, by = ...): keep only matching rows from both datasets
  • left_join(x, y, by = ...): keep all rows from x, add matches from y
  • right_join(x, y, by = ...): keep all rows from y, add matches from x
  • full_join(x, y, by = ...): keep all rows from both x and y (union)
  • anti_join(x, y, by = ...): keep rows from x that do not have a match in y
  • semi_join(x, y, by = ...): keep rows from x that do have a match in y (but don’t add y’s columns)

inner_join(): example data

Let’s create some example data for inner_join visualization:

x <- tibble(
  id = c(1, 2, 3),
  value_x = c("x1", "x2", "x3")
)

y <- tibble(
  id = c(1, 2, 4),
  value_y = c("y1", "y2", "y4")
)

inner_join(): in action

keep only matching rows from both datasets

inner_join(x, y, by = "id")
## # A tibble: 2 × 3
##      id value_x value_y
##   <dbl> <chr>   <chr>  
## 1     1 x1      y1     
## 2     2 x2      y2

left_join(): in action

keep all rows from x, add matches from y

left_join(x, y, by = "id")
## # A tibble: 3 × 3
##      id value_x value_y
##   <dbl> <chr>   <chr>  
## 1     1 x1      y1     
## 2     2 x2      y2     
## 3     3 x3      <NA>

left_join(): example data y with extra row

Let’s create some example data for left_join visualization, but this time y has an additional row:

x <- tibble(
  id = c(1, 2, 3),
  value_x = c("x1", "x2", "x3")
)

y <- tibble(
  id = c(1, 2, 2, 4),
  value_y = c("y1", "y2", "y2", "y4")
)

left_join(): in action

keep all rows from x, add matches from y

inner_join(x, y, by = "id")
## # A tibble: 3 × 3
##      id value_x value_y
##   <dbl> <chr>   <chr>  
## 1     1 x1      y1     
## 2     2 x2      y2     
## 3     2 x2      y2

right_join(): in action

keep all rows from y, add matches from x (equal to left_join(y, x, by = "id"))

right_join(x, y, by = "id") 
## # A tibble: 3 × 3
##      id value_x value_y
##   <dbl> <chr>   <chr>  
## 1     1 x1      y1     
## 2     2 x2      y2     
## 3     4 <NA>    y4

full_join(): in action

keep all rows from both x and y (union)

full_join(x, y, by = "id")
## # A tibble: 4 × 3
##      id value_x value_y
##   <dbl> <chr>   <chr>  
## 1     1 x1      y1     
## 2     2 x2      y2     
## 3     3 x3      <NA>   
## 4     4 <NA>    y4

anti_join(): in action

keep rows from x that do not have a match in y

anti_join(x, y, by = "id")
## # A tibble: 1 × 2
##      id value_x
##   <dbl> <chr>  
## 1     3 x3

semi_join(): in action

keep all rows from x where there are matching values in y, keeping just columns from x

similar to inner_join(), but only keep values in x

semi_join(x, y, by = "id")
## # A tibble: 2 × 2
##      id value_x
##   <dbl> <chr>  
## 1     1 x1     
## 2     2 x2

tidyr: data reshaping

  • converts data format
    • pivot_longer(): converts data from wide to long format
    • pivor_wider(): converts data from long to wide format

what are the long format and wide format?

wide and long format

tidyr: generate example data

wide <- tibble(
  id = c(1, 2),
  x  = c("a", "b"),
  y  = c("c", "d"),
  z  = c("e", "f")
)
wide
## # A tibble: 2 × 4
##      id x     y     z    
##   <dbl> <chr> <chr> <chr>
## 1     1 a     c     e    
## 2     2 b     d     f

pivot_longer() in action

Usage:

pivot_longer(data, cols = <colname_start>:<colname_end>, names_to = "key", values_to = "val")
long <- pivot_longer(wide, cols = x:z, names_to = "key", values_to = "val")
long
## # A tibble: 6 × 3
##      id key   val  
##   <dbl> <chr> <chr>
## 1     1 x     a    
## 2     1 y     c    
## 3     1 z     e    
## 4     2 x     b    
## 5     2 y     d    
## 6     2 z     f

pivot_wider(): in action

Usage:

pivot_wider(data, names_from = key, values_from = val)
pivot_wider(long, names_from = key, values_from = val)
## # A tibble: 2 × 4
##      id x     y     z    
##   <dbl> <chr> <chr> <chr>
## 1     1 a     c     e    
## 2     2 b     d     f
